rmk: from:"Some Skomer sounds", 2004, Rombout de Wijs. In 1982 and 1983 I was a research assistant on Skomer Island for counting, observing and ringing seabirds. In my spare time I made many pictures and also recoded sounds of several birds. The main purpose was to document the state of island life at that time, also enabling me to relive my stay (to some extent) in later years. Sound recordings were made with rather primitive means, two simple microphones mounted in the "focal point" of a plastic umbrella (used as a reflector), a Sony TCS-310 stereo cassette recorder and simple headphones. Only recently I decided to make them better available and therefore digitized them. From 3.5 hours of sounds I extracted this selection for audio cd.

file-name: XC319352-160517 Z06 Tr34 Skokholm Manx Shearw colony flight.mp3
rmk: Many females (harsh low pitched) and fewer males (vibrato high pitched) are heard. The thousands of Shearwaters arrive from the sea in the black night flying around to locate the nest-holes. They cry out loud while orientating and locating among the thousands of burrows in the large colony (by both smell and hearing??). They tumble down in the soft grass and can probably recognize voices from the answering mate in the nest-hole and from recognizing neighbour individuals calling in the sound-landscape. The darkness protect the shearwaters during their clumsy landings  near the nests from the Great Black-backed Gulls, hanging above like sharks. A breeding colony of 45.000 pairs. Recorded with pair of Røde NTG3 and Zoom H6.

file-name: XC189581-Manx Shearwaters, noisy track, Big Copeland 2014-08-01;0108.mp3
rmk: Recordings feature Manx Shearwaters calling from a network of burrows. Apart from what sound like airborne birds within the first 30 seconds, all other voices originate from birds in burrows. I was lying on the ground beside the burrows and I do not know what caused this spectacular 'domino effect' of a burst of calling from several birds. Based on speculation on criteria for how the voices of the sexes can be distinguished (in the text accompanying XC189554) it seems feasible to apportion the following voices as follows: flying male 0:21 (for seven seconds); female 0:31 (for four seconds); male 0:39 (for two seconds); female 0:41 (for five seconds); different female (or possibly male) 0:46 (for four seconds); loud female 0:52 (for six seconds); loudest female 1:01 (for eight seconds); male 1:17 (for five seconds); from 1:23 onwards, possibly only female voices to end of recording.  Another recording can be heard at XC189575.

file-name: XC189575-Manx Shearwater, burrow calls, Big Copeland 2014-07-31; 1156.mp3
rmk:
This recording was made during several hours spent at a colony (for more information - especially about the subtly different voices of males and females - please read the text accompanying XC189554). The circumstances of this recording need a short explanation. I was lying among Bracken and Himalayan Balsam and placed my recorder (Olympus LS11) at the mouth of an occupied burrow. I shone a torch inside the burrow and was just about able to see part of an adult. Was it alone? What was its sex? Did it have a chick or was it simply prospecting? I do not have answers to any of those questions - all of which have a bearing on the recorded vocals. The ground below me was 'alive' with sounds. Birds were calling from burrows everywhere. I could not see the burrows as they were among vegetation. At this stage of the evening more sound was coming from below ground than was being delivered from flying birds. However, as the night worn on, aerial callers became the main source of sound - possibly because their voices dominated the airwaves. Each burrow that had a tenant was not necessarily vocal. Hence, there was a randomness to where calls originated. I simply waited for sound to issue from the burrow featured in this recording. In the clip, an airborne male calls first. I did not see the bird as I was lying down. In fact, I'm assuming the male was in flight. Possibly it was on the ground. However, at 0:12, sounds commence from the burrow. From here on, all sounds come from the burrow. My great friend Neville McKee, who has studied the Manx Shearwaters on the Copeland Islands since at least 1960 (!) has commented: 'Underground breeders may murmur to the chick, which can give a little whispering soft hiss in reply. Breeders may also whisper to each other in the fairly rare event of both being in the burrow to feed the chick at the same time. All other underground calling is pair bonding between pre-breeders establishing ownership of the burrow. Sometimes there can be angry sounds due to breeders chasing out a non-breeding intruder. The muffled sound can become loud if the adult emerges from the burrow in an effort to drive away the intruder.'
In light of Neville's comments, I am not sure what was behind the recorded calls. Other recordings of more easily interpreted calls are XC189581 and XC189554.

file-name: XC189554-Manx Shearwaters, airborne calls, Big Copeland 2014-08-01,0120.mp3
rmk: Manx Shearwaters calling in darkness above breeding burrows among waist-high vegetation consisting of bracken and Himalayan Balsam. Male and female calls, although proven by research to be subtly different [James, Paul C, 1985, The vocal behaviour of the Manx Shearwater, Zeitschrift fur Tierpsychologie 67: 269-283] are challenging when an inexperienced recordist is tested in total darkness among many whirling, calling birds! Males are higher-pitched than females. Immature birds are responsible for the majority of the calling (Neville McKee. pers obs). Male calling predominates at ground level and female calling predominates in flight (James, op cit). The caterwauling concert is a result of non-breeders visiting a colony and attempting to locate a vacant burrow (in the case of males) or find a mate who happens to have a burrow (in the case of females). For this reason, most calls from ground level are given by males; most airborne callers are females. The communication is designed to bring prospective partners into contact. I found that the sheer variation in sounds made it difficult to always make an equivocal distinction between males and females. However, many did seem to be distinguishable. Although how do I know for sure? Male voices were 'more melodic', the notes were more clearly enunciated (and fairly leisurely) and the nicest of them had a 'laughing gas' quality. Female voices were hoarse and asthmatic and the notes often seemed to accelerate and increase in volume. In this recording I have attempted to annotate some of the calls and speculate that the following timestamps might refer to each sex: female 0:06 (for next four seconds); male 0:28 (for next seven seconds); female 0:57 (until end of first minute); female 1:03 (for next two seconds); male 1:20 (for next four seconds); female 1:40 (for next four seconds); male 1:48 (until, four seconds later, clip ends). Further calls can be heard at XC189575 and XC18981.
